## Chapter Fourier Analysis

of Discrete-Time Systems

### 1 Introduction

In the previous chapter, we considered techniques for the time-domain analysis of discrete-time systems. Recall that, as in the case of continuous-time systems, the primary characterization of a linear time-invariant discrete-time system that we used was in terms of the response of the system to the unit impulse. In this and subsequent chapters, we consider frequency-domain techniques for analyzing discrete-time systems. We start our discussion of these techniques with a consideration of the Fourier analysis of discrete-time signals. As we might suspect, the results that we obtain closely parallel those for continuous-time systems.

To motivate our discussion of frequency-domain techniques, let us consider the response of a linear time-invariant discrete-time system to a complex exponential input of the form

\[x\left(n\right)=z^{n} \tag{1.1.1}\]

where \(z\) is a complex number. If the impulse response of the system is \(h\left(n\right)\), the output of the system is determined by the convolution sum as

\[y\left(n\right) =\sum_{k\,=\,-\infty}^{\infty}h\left(k\right)x\left(n\,-\,k\right)\] \[=\sum_{k\,=\,-\infty}^{\infty}h\left(k\right)z^{n\,-\,k}\] \[=z^{n}\sum_{k\,=\,-\,-\infty}^{\infty}h\left(k\right)z^{-\,k} \tag{1.1.2}\]

For a fixed \(z\), the summation is just a constant, which we denote by \(H\left(z\right)\), that is,\[H\left(z\right)=\sum_{k\,=\,-\,\infty}^{\infty}h\left(k\right)z^{-k} \tag{7.1.3}\]

so that

\[y\left(n\right)=H\left(z\right)x\left(n\right) \tag{7.1.4}\]

As can be seen from Equation (7.1.4), output \(y\left(n\right)\) is just input \(x\left(n\right)\) multiplied by scaling factor \(H\left(z\right)\).

We can extend this result to the case where the input to the system consists of a linear combination of complex exponentials of the form of Equation (7.1.1). Specifically, let

\[x\left(n\right)=\sum_{k\,=\,1}^{N}a_{k}\,z_{k}^{n} \tag{7.1.5}\]

It follows from the superposition property and Equation (7.1.3) that the ouput is given by

\[y\left(n\right) =\sum_{k\,=\,1}^{N}a_{k}\,H\left(z_{k}\right)\,z_{k}^{n}\] \[=\sum_{k\,=\,1}^{N}b_{k}\,z_{k}^{n} \tag{7.1.6}\]

That is, the output is also a linear combination of the complex exponentials in the input. Coefficient \(b_{k}\) associated with function \(z_{k}^{n}\) in the output is just the corresponding coefficient \(a_{k}\) multiplied by scaling factor \(H\left(z_{k}\right)\).

**Example 7.1.1**: We want to find the output of the system with impulse response

\[h\left(n\right)=(\frac{1}{2})^{n}u\left(n\right)\]

when the input is

\[x\left(n\right)=2\,\cos\,\,\frac{2\pi}{3}\,\,n\]

To find the output, we first find \(H\left(z\right)\) as

\[H\left(z\right)=\sum_{n\,=\,0}^{\infty}\,(\frac{1}{2})^{n}z^{-n}=\sum_{n\,=\, 0}^{\infty}\,(\frac{1}{2}\,z^{-1})^{n}=\frac{1}{1-\frac{1}{2}\,\,z^{-1}}\]

where we have used Equation (6.3.7). The input can be expressed as

\[x\left(n\right)=\exp\left[j\frac{2\pi}{3}n\,\right]+\exp\left[-j\frac{2\pi}{ 3}n\,\right]\]

so that we have

\[z_{1}=\exp\left[j\frac{2\pi}{3}\right],\qquad z_{2}=\exp\left[-j\frac{2\pi}{ 3}\right],\qquad a_{1}=a_{2}=1\]and

\[H(z_{1})=\frac{1}{1-\frac{1}{2}\,\exp\left[\,-j(2\pi/3)\right]}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{7}} \,\exp\left[\,-j\phi\right],\]

\[H(z_{2})=\frac{1}{1-\frac{1}{2}\,\exp\left[\,j(2\pi/3)\right]}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{7} }\,\exp\left[\,j\phi\right],\qquad\phi=\tan^{-1}\,\frac{\sqrt{3}}{5}\]

It follows from Equation (7.1.5) that the output is given by

\[y\left(n\right) =\frac{2}{\sqrt{7}}\,\exp\left[\,j\phi\right]\,\exp\left[\,j\frac{ 2\pi}{3}\,\,n\,\right]+\frac{2}{\sqrt{7}}\,\exp\left[\,-j\frac{2\pi}{3}\,\,n\,\right]\] \[=3\,\cos(\frac{2\pi}{3}\,\,n\,+\phi)\]

A special case is where the input is of the form \(\exp\left[\,j\Omega_{k}\right]\), where \(\Omega_{k}\) is a real continuous variable. This corresponds to the case \(\left|\,z_{k}\,\right|=1\). For this input, the output is given by

\[y\left(n\right)=H(e^{j\Omega k})\,\exp\left[\,j\Omega_{k}n\,\right] \tag{7.1.7}\]

where, from Equation (7.1.3),

\[H(e^{j\Omega})=H\left(\Omega\right)=\sum_{n\,=\,-\,-\,\infty}^{\infty}h\left( n\right)\exp\left[\,-j\Omega n\,\right] \tag{7.1.8}\]

### Fourier-Series Representation of Discrete-Time Periodic Signals

Often, as we have seen in our considerations of continuous-time systems, we are interested in the response of linear systems to periodic inputs. We recall that a discrete-time signal \(x\left(n\right)\) is periodic with period \(N\), if

\[x\left(n\right)=x\left(n\,+\,N\right) \tag{7.2.1}\]

for \(N\) some positive integer. It follows from our discussion in the previous section that if \(x\left(n\right)\) can be expressed as the sum of several complex exponentials, the response of the system is easily determined. In analogy with our representation of periodic signals in continuous time, we can expect that we can obtain such a representation in terms of the harmonics corresponding to the fundamental frequency \(2\pi/N\). That is, we seek a representation for \(x\left(n\right)\), of the form

\[x\left(n\right)=\sum_{k}a_{k}\,\exp\left[\,j\Omega_{k}n\,\right]=\sum_{k}a_{k }\,x_{k}\left(n\right) \tag{7.2.2}\]

where \(\Omega_{k}=2\pi k/N\). It is clear that \(x_{k}\left(n\right)\) are periodic since \(\Omega_{k}/2\pi\) is a rational number. We also recall from our discussions in Chapter 6 that there are only \(N\) distinct waveforms in this set corresponding to \(k=0\), \(1\), \(2\,\ldots\,N-1\) since 

where \(\delta(m-k-rN)\) is the unit sample occurring at \(m=k+rN\). Substitution in Equation (7.2.7) then yields

\[\sum_{n\,=\,0}^{N\,-\,1}x\,(n)\,\exp\,[-j\frac{2\pi}{N}kn\,]=\sum_{m\,=\,<N>}Na_{ m}\,\,\delta(m-k\,-rN) \tag{7.2.13}\]

Since the summation on the right is carried out over \(N\) consecutive values of \(m\) for a fixed value of \(k\), it is clear that the only value that \(r\) can take in the range of summation is \(r=0\). Thus, the only nonzero value in the sum corresponds to \(m=k\) and the right-hand side of Equation (7.2.13) evaluates to \(Na_{k}\), so that

\[a_{k}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n\,=\,0}^{N\,-\,1}x\,(n)\,\exp\,[\,-j\frac{2\pi}{N}kn\,] \tag{7.2.14}\]

Because each of the terms in the summation in Equation (7.2.14) is periodic with period \(N\), the summation can be taken over any \(N\) successive values of \(n\). We thus have the pair of equations

\[x\,(n)=\sum_{k\,=\,<N>}a_{k}\,\exp\,[\,j\,\,\frac{2\pi}{N}\,\,kn\,] \tag{7.2.15}\]

\[a_{k}=\frac{1}{N}\,\sum_{n\,=\,<N>}x\,(n)\,\exp\,[\,-j\,\,\frac{2\pi}{N}\,\, kn\,] \tag{7.2.16}\]

which together form the discrete-time Fourier-series pair.

Since \(x_{k+N}(n)=x_{k}(n)\), it is clear that

\[a_{k+N}=a_{k} \tag{7.2.17}\]

Since the Fourier series for discrete-time periodic signals is a finite sum defined entirely by the values of the signal over one period, the series always converges. The Fourier series provides an _exact_ alternate representation of the time signal and issues such as convergence or the Gibbs phenomenon do not arise.

