### 7.3 The Discrete-Time Fourier Transform

We now consider the frequency-domain representation of discrete-time signals that are not necessarily periodic. For continuous-time signals, we obtained such a representation by defining the Fourier transform of a signal \(x\left(t\right)\) as

\[X\left(\omega\right)=\mathcal{F}\left\{x\left(t\right)\right\}=\int\limits_{- \infty}^{\infty}\,x\left(t\right)\,\exp\left[\,-j\omega t\,\right]\,dt \tag{7.3.1}\]with respect to the transform (frequency) variable \(\omega\). For discrete-time signals, we consider an analogous definition of the Fourier transform as

\[X\left(\Omega\right)=\mathscr{T}\left\{x\left(n\right)\right\}=\sum_{n\,=\,-\, \infty}^{\infty}x\left(n\right)\,\exp\left[\,-j\Omega n\,\right] \tag{7.3.2}\]

where the transform variable is now equal to \(\Omega\). The transform exists if \(x\left(n\right)\) satisfies a relation of the type

\[\sum_{n\,=\,-\,\infty}^{\infty}\,|x\left(n\right)|\,<\,\infty\qquad\text{or} \qquad\sum_{n\,=\,-\,\infty}^{\infty}\,|x\left(n\right)|^{\,2}\,<\,\infty \tag{7.3.3}\]

These 'conditions are sufficient to guarantee that the sequence has a discrete-time Fourier transform. As in the case of continuous-time signals, there are signals that are neither absolutely summable or have finite energy, but still have discrete-time Fourier transforms.

We reiterate that although \(\omega\) has units of radians/second, \(\Omega\) has units of radians. Since \(\exp\left[\,j\Omega n\,\right]\) is periodic with period \(2\pi\), it follows that \(X\left(\Omega\right)\) is also periodic with the same period, since

\[X\left(\Omega+2\pi\right) =\sum_{n\,=\,-\,\infty}^{\infty}x\left(n\right)\,\exp\left[\,-j \left(\Omega+2\pi\right)n\,\right]\] \[=\sum_{n\,=\,-\,\infty}^{\infty\infty}x\left(n\right)\,\exp \left[\,-j\Omega n\,\right]=X\left(\Omega\right) \tag{7.3.4}\]

As a consequence, while in the continuous-time case, we have to consider values of \(\omega\) over the entire real axis, in the discrete-time case, we have to consider values of \(\Omega\) only over the range \([0,\,2\pi]\).

To find the inverse relation between \(X\left(\Omega\right)\) and \(x\left(n\right)\), we replace the variable \(n\) in Equation (7.3.2) by \(p\) to get

\[X\left(\Omega\right)=\sum_{p\,=\,-\,\infty}^{\infty\,\infty}x\left(p\right)\, \exp\left[\,-j\Omega p\,\right] \tag{7.3.5}\]

Now multiply both sides of Equation (7.3.5) by \(\exp\left[\,j\Omega n\,\right]\) and integrate over the range \([0,\,2\pi]\) to get

\[\int\limits_{\Omega\,=\,0}^{2\pi}X\left(\Omega\right)\,\exp\left[\,j\Omega n \,\right]\,d\Omega=\int\limits_{\Omega\,=\,0}^{2\pi}\sum_{p\,=\,-\,\infty}^{ \infty\,\infty}x\left(p\right)\,\exp\left[\,j\Omega\left(n-p\right)\right]\,d\Omega \tag{7.3.6}\]

Interchanging the orders of summation and integration on the right side of Equation (7.3.6) then gives

\[\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}X\left(\Omega\right)\,\exp\left[\,j\Omega n\,\right]\,d \Omega=\sum_{p\,=\,-\,\infty}^{\infty\,\infty}x\left(p\right)\int\limits_{0} ^{2\pi}\exp\left[\,j\Omega\left(n-p\right)\right]\,d\Omega \tag{7.3.7}\]

It can be verified (see Problem 7.10) that

\[\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}\exp\left[\,j\Omega\left(n-p\right)\right]\,d\Omega= \begin{cases}2\pi,&n=p\\ 0,&n\neq p\end{cases} \tag{7.3.8}\]so that the right-hand side of Equation (7.3.7) evaluates to \(2\pi x\left(n\right)\). We can, therefore, write

\[x\left(n\right)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int\limits_{0}^{2\pi}X\left(\Omega\right)\,\exp \left[\,j\Omega n\,\right]\,d\Omega \tag{7.3.9}\]

Again, since the integrand in Equation (7.3.9) is periodic with period \(2\pi\), the integration can be carried out over any interval of length \(2\pi\). The discrete-time Fourier-transform relations, therefore, can be written as

\[X\left(\Omega\right) =\sum\limits_{n\,=\,-\infty}^{\infty\infty}x\left(n\right)\,\exp \left[\,-j\Omega n\,\right] \tag{7.3.10}\] \[x\left(n\right) =\frac{1}{2\pi}\int\limits_{<2\pi>}X\left(\Omega\right)\exp \left[\,j\Omega n\,\right]\,d\Omega \tag{7.3.11}\]

We consider a few examples.

**Example 7.3.1**: Consider the sequence

\[x\left(n\right)=\alpha^{n}\,u\left(n\right),\qquad\left|\alpha\right|\,<1\]

For this example,

\[X\left(\Omega\right)=\sum\limits_{n\,=\,0}^{\infty}\alpha^{n}\,\exp\left[\,-j \Omega n\,\right]=\frac{1}{1-\alpha\,\exp\left[\,-j\Omega\right]}\]

The magnitude is given by

\[\left|X\left(\Omega\right)\right|\,=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+\alpha^{2}-2\alpha\,\cos \,\Omega}}\]

and the phase by

\[\mathrm{Arg}\,X\left(\Omega\right)=-\mathrm{tan}^{-1}\,\,\,\frac{\alpha\,\sin \,\Omega}{1-\alpha\,\cos\,\Omega}\]

