### Summary

* A periodic discrete-time signal \(x(n)\) with period \(N\) can be represented by the discrete-time Fourier series (DTFS) \[x(n)=\sum_{k\,=\,0}^{N-1}a_{k}\,\exp{\,[\,j\frac{2\pi}{N}kn\,]}.\]
* The DTFS coefficients \(a_{k}\) are given by \[a_{k}=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n\,=\,0}^{N-1}x(n)\,\exp{\,[-j\frac{2\pi}{N}kn\,]}\]
* Coefficients \(a_{k}\) are periodic with period \(N\), so that \(a_{k}=a_{k}+N\).
* The DTFS is a finite sum over only \(N\) terms. It provides an _exact_ alternate representation of the time signal and issues such as convergence or the Gibbs phenomenon do not arise.
* If \(a_{k}\) are the DTFS coefficients of signal \(x(n)\), then the coefficients for \(x(n-m)\) are equal to \(a_{k}\exp{\,[-j(2\pi/N)km\,]}\).

