* If the periodic sequence \(x\left(n\right)\) with DTFS coefficients \(a_{k}\) is input to a LTI system with impulse response \(h\left(n\right)\), the DTFS coefficients \(b_{k}\) of the output \(y\left(n\right)\), are given by \[b_{k}=a_{k}\,H\left(\frac{2\pi}{N}k\right)\] where \[H\left(\Omega\right)=\sum_{n\,=\,-\infty}^{\infty}h\left(n\right)\,\exp\left[ \,-j\Omega n\,\right]\]
* The discrete-time Fourier transform (DTFT) of an aperiodic sequence \(x\left(n\right)\) is given by \[X\left(\Omega\right)=\sum_{n\,=\,-\infty}^{\infty}x\left(n\right)\exp[-j\Omega n\,]\]
* The inverse relationship is given by \[x\left(n\right)=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi}X\left(\Omega\right)\exp\left[\, j\Omega n\,\right]\,d\Omega\]
* The DTFT variable \(\Omega\) has units of radians.
* The DTFT is periodic in \(\Omega\) with period \(2\pi\) so that \(X\left(\Omega\right)=X\left(\Omega+2\pi\right)\).
* Other properties are similar to that of the continuous-time Fourier transform. In particular, if \(y\left(n\right)\) is the convolution of \(x\left(n\right)\) and \(h\left(n\right)\), then, \[Y\left(\Omega\right)=H\left(\Omega\right)X\left(\Omega\right)\]
* When analog signal \(x_{a}(t)\) is sampled, the resulting signal can be considered to be either a CT signal \(x_{s}(t)\) with Fourier transform \(X_{s}(\omega)\) or a DT sequence \(x\left(n\right)\) with DTFT \(X\left(\Omega\right)\). The relation between the two is given by \[X_{s}(\omega)=X\left(\Omega\right)\big{|}_{\Omega\,=\,\omega\,T}\]
* This equation can be used to derive the impulse modulation model for sampling: \[x_{s}(t)=x_{a}(t)\sum_{n\,=\,-\infty}^{\infty}\delta(t\,-nT)\]
* Transform \(X_{s}(\omega)\) is related to \(X_{a}(\omega)\) by \[X_{s}(\omega)=\frac{1}{T}\sum_{r\,=\,-\infty}^{\infty}X_{a}(\omega+\,r\,\omega _{s})\]
* We can use the last equation to derive the _sampling theorem_, which gives the minimum rate at which an analog signal must be sampled to permit error-free reconstruction. If the signal has a bandwidth of \(\omega_{c}\), then \(T<2\pi/\omega_{c}\).